      "rationale": "GCI was computed for 3 of 5 operating points. At the two highest flow-speed combinations, grid convergence was not fully demonstrated due to computational resource constraints. Achieved level falls short of MRL 5 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match VAD operating envelope including hematocrit, temperature, and anticoagulation protocol with full traceability.",
      "rationale": "Available experimental data used bench-scale conditions with bovine blood at hematocrit levels not fully representative of the clinical VAD population. Temperature and anticoagulation protocols differ from intended COU. This represents a major gap for absolute hemolysis threshold comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., normalized RMS error, band of equivalence) applied to hemolysis index predictions versus measured values across all operating points.",
      "rationale": "Qualitative agreement was demonstrated for relative trends in hemolysis index, but quantitative band-of-equivalence analysis was not performed. The absolute hemolysis index predictions deviate by up to 40% from experimental measurements at high-shear operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstrated that the computed hemolysis index (HI) is the direct clinical QoI and that intermediate flow quantities used to derive HI are validated.",
      "rationale": "The hemolysis index is correctly identified as the primary QoI. Intermediate quantities (shear stress, exposure time) are partially validated through PIV comparison, but the mapping from shear stress to HI via the power-law model introduces unvalidated model-form uncertainty at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
